http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/%E2%80%98Have-a-lot-to-learn-from-China%E2%80%99/article13989653.ece

Chief Minister K. Chandrasekhar Rao has said India has to learn more than a lesson or two from China that had overcome backwardness by changing itself into a hardcore capitalist economy from a communist-socialist society.Speaking at the 27{+t}{+h}All India Builders’ convention being held at Ramoji Film City here on Friday, he said the country needs to be on alert in attracting investments in the backdrop of a healthy growth of economy and reforms’ path. “We need to facilitate investment and create wealth as China did,” Mr. Rao said adding that over 50 delegations from as many country had visited Telangana after he had taken over as Chief Minister to explore the investment opportunities.“Till the time of Mao Zedong, China was more backward than India, but the whole change was brought about by Deng Xiaoping who transformed the Chinese economy with far-reaching initiatives toward market-driven economy,” Mr. Rao explained.Builders from Hyderabad and surrounding areas had made name for themselves across the country and outside, the Chief Minister said adding that the new Parliament building in Afghanistan, a tunnel in Jammu & Kashmir and several prestigious projects across the country were all executed by them. He stated that building (construction) industry was the second largest employment provider in the country after agriculture sector.On the initiatives of Telangana, the Chief Minister said they had to issue GO 123 to buy land required for project, not acquisition, and added that the land required for Palamuru-Rangareddy irrigation project was ready with the government before the tenders were floated.Union Minister for Urban Development M. Venkaiah Naidu said construction of 10,000 km of roads in the country would be taken up in the next financial year and asked the builders to be part of Make in India and Swachh Bharat programmes of the Centre.He said that had met Congress president Sonia Gandhi seeking cooperation in passing GST and Real Estate Bills in the budget session of Parliament.